INVESTIGATION OF,@95-97@ CIA RELEASED UNCLASSIFIED VERSION OF GATES PANEL REVIEW OF NIE 95-19. NIE 95-19 FAR FROM POLITICIZING THIS ESTIMATE~ SENIOR INTEL COMMUNITY MANAGERS FAILED ADEQUATELY TO ALERT ANALYSTS TO THE SENSITIVITY OF THIS ESTIMATES... ONE OF MAIN CHARGES MADE AGAINST CIA ON THIS WAS NOT SIMPLY THAT REPORT ITSELF WAS BIASED~ BUT THAT LEAKING ITS CONTENTS TO DEMOCRATIC OPPONENTS OF MISSILE DEFENSE WAS POLITICAL. IT WAS A CASE OF CLINTON ADM~ NOT WANTING MISSILE DEFENSE~ LEAKING A TOP SECRET INTEL REPORT THAT SUPPORTED ITS POSITION...PANEL BELIEVES INTEL COMMUNITY HAS A STRONG CASE THAT~ FOR SOUND TECHNICAL REASONS~ U.S. IS UNLIKELY TO FACE AN INDIGENOUSLY DEVELOPED AND TESTED INTERCONTINENTAL BALLISTIC MISSILE THREAT FROM THE THIRD WORLD BEFORE 2010~ EVEN TAKING INTO ACCOUNT ACQUISITION OF FOREIGN HARDWARE AND TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE. CASE IS EVEN STRONGER THAN PRESENTED IN THE NIE. OTHER CHARGE MADE AT THE TIME WAS THAT THE REPORT WAS TOO NARROWLY FOCUSED ONLY ON THOSE COUNTRIES THAT COULD BUILD THEIR OWN ICBMS FROM SCRATCH AND DID NOT INCLUDE THOSE COUNTRIES THAT MIGHT BUY THEM FROM SOMEONE ELSE. WAYNEDAY@GWIS2.CIRC.GWU.EDU 1/24/97
INVESTIGATION OF,@95-99@ CROWE COMMISSION INVESTIGATION INTO WHY TWO U.S. EMBASSIES IN AFRICA WERE VULNERABLE ISSUED A SCATHING REPORT~ CRITICIZING ^THE COLLECTIVE FAILURE OVER THE PAST DECADE^ TO PREPARE FOR AND TO ADEQUATELY FUND IMPROVEMENTS AT AMERICAN EMBASSIES. REPORT NOTES U.S. INTEL DETECTED A NUMBER OF THREATS AGAINST THE EMBASSIES IN NAIROBI AND DAR ES SALAAM IN THE TWO YEARS BEFORE THE NEARLY SIMULTANEOUS BOMBINGS LAST AUG. 7. BUT THE INTELLIGENCE WAS TOO VAGUE TO BE VERY USEFUL. U.S. OFFICIALS HAVE BEEN TOO RELIANT ON SUCH ^WARNING INTELLIGENCE~^ AND RELAXED IN THE ABSENCE OF INTELLIGENCE REPORTS DESCRIBING SPECIFIC DANGERS. HARSHEST CRITICISM WAS FOR THE FAILURE TO CONTEMPLATE THE TYPE OF TRUCK BOMBS~ IN LIGHT OF THE 1996 TRUCK BOMBING OF A U.S. AIR FORCE DORMITORY IN SAUDI ARABIA~ AND THE DESTRUCTION OF THE U.S. MARINE BARRACKS AND THE U.S. EMBASSY IN BEIRUT IN 1983. PANEL RECOMMENDED SPENDING $1.4 BILLION A YEAR OVER 10 YEARS TO IMPROVE SECURITY AT U.S. DIPLOMATIC MISSIONS. AMONG ITS OTHER PROPOSALS WAS ONE TO BRING ALL OVERSEAS FACILITIES UP TO THE STANDARDS. REPORT CONCLUDED THAT ^SYSTEMIC AND INSTITUTIONAL FAILURES RESPONSIBLE FOR A FLAWED PROCESS FOR ASSESSING THREAT LEVELS WORLDWIDE WHICH UNDERESTIMATED THE THREAT OF TERRORISM...^ THERE WAS NO CREDIBLE INTEL WARNING OF THE AUG. 7 BOMBINGS. A NUMBER OF EARLIER REPORTS CITED ALLEGED THREATS AGAINST SEVERAL U.S. DIPLOMATIC AND OTHER TARGETS~ INCLUDING THE EMBASSIES IN NAIROBI AND DAR ES SALAAM... BUT WERE LARGELY DISCOUNTED BECAUSE OF DOUBTS ABOUT THE SOURCES. OTHER REPORTING~ WAS IMPRECISE~ CHANGING AND NONSPECIFIC AS TO DATES~ DIMINISHING ITS USEFULNESS.^ <WP 1/8/99 A1
