INVESTIGATION OF,GUATEMALA~ @76-96@ JOINT STATEMENT RE GUATEMALA INVESTIGATION BY THE INTEL OVERSIGHT BOARD. A NUMBER OF ISSUES MUST BE ADDRESSED: 1. PARAMETERS OF IOB INVESTIGATION FOCUSED ON A NARROW SET OF CASES IN WHICH U.S. CITIZENS OR THEIR RELATIVES WERE THE VICTIMS OF HUMAN RIGHTS VIOLATIONS NOT VIOLATIONS OF GUATEMALAN HUMAN RIGHTS BY INTEL AGENTS EMPLOYED OR CONTRACTED BY U.S. INTEL. 2. THE IOB INVESTIGATION RESTRICTED THE TIME PERIOD TO SPECIFIC CASES AFTER 1984. 3. THE IOB REPORT DID NOT ADEQUATELY ADDRESS THE RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN THE U.S. AND GUATEMALA. 4. REPORT DID NOT ADDRESS THE EFFECT OF THE RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN THE U.S. AND GUATEMALA ON STATE DEPARTMENT'S HUMAN RIGHTS REPORTING. 5. THE REPORT LOOKS ONLY AT GUATEMALA NOT U.S. INTEL TIES WITH AND PAYMENTS TO HUMAN RIGHTS ABUSERS THROUGHOUT THE HEMISPHERE. 6. THE ^PUBLIC SUMMARY^ OF THE IOB REPORT IS NOT A SUBSTITUTE FOR THE DISCLOSURE OF THE FULL REPORT AND THE REPORTS OF THE CIA INSPECTOR GENERAL~ THE DEPARTMENT OF STATE~ THE DEPARTMENT OF DEFENSE~ THE DEPARTMENT OF JUSTICE~ AND THE FBI. PROTECTION OF ^SOURCES AND METHODS^ SHOULD NOT BE USED TO SHIELD HUMAN RIGHTS VIOLATORS. 7. FULL DECLASSIFICATION OF U.S. DOCUMENTS RELEVANT TO HUMAN RIGHTS INVESTIGATIONS IS ESSENTIAL. EPICA <EPICA@IGC.APC.ORG> 6/28/96
