INVESTIGATION OF,IN @48-49@ TWO IMPORTANT INVESTIGATIONS CONDUCTED. ONE~ THE EBERSTADT COMMITTEE'S REPORT TO THE HOOVER COMMISSION ON THE ORGANIZATION OF THE EXECUTIVE BRANCH OF GVT~ WAS SPONSORED BY CONGRESS. THE OTHER~ THE DULLES REPORT OF THE INTELLIGENCE SURVEY GROUP~ WAS INITIATED BY THE NSC. THE EBERSTADT REPORT SUPPORTED INTEGRATION OF ALL CLANDESTINE OPS IN THE CIA UNDER THE NSC'S SUPERVISION. IN WARTIME THE OPERATIONAL SERVICES WOULD BE TRANSFERRED TO THE JCS. THE DULLES REPORT (OFTEN REFERRED TO AS THE DULLES-JACKSON-CORREA REPORT) WAS LINKED TO EFFORTS BY THE STATE DEPARTMENT TO HAVE COVERT OPS PUT UNDER ITS GUIDANCE. INTEL SURVEY GROUP ESTABLISHED BY THE NSC ON 8 JAN 48. GROUPS CONSISTED OF ALLEN DULLES AS CHAIRMAN~ MATTHIAS CORREA~ AND WILLIAM JACKSON. THEY ASSISTED BY ROBERT BLUM~ AN ASSISTANT OF DEFENSE SECRETARY FORRESTAL. REPORT ACCUSED THE TOP OFFICIALS OF CIA WITH LACK OF LEADERSHIP. GALLOWAY AND WRIGHT LEFT. TCIA INTRO CHAPTER VIII. EBERSTADT REPORT ALMOST IMMEDIATELY ECLIPSED BY THE INTEL SURVEY GROUP AKA DULLES REPORT. <TCIA 284
INVESTIGATION OF,IN @48@ DULLES-JACKSON-CORREA SURVEY COMMISSIONED BY NSC. REPORT SAID THAT INSTEAD OF COORDINATING INTEL~ CIA HAD BECOME JUST ANOTHER INTEL AGENCY IN COMPETITION WITH ESTABLISHED AGENCIES. ITS DIRECTOR WAS NOT IN INTIMATE CONTACT WITH DAY-TO-DAY OPS~ HE PROVIDED NO POLICY GUIDANCE~ AND SURROUNDED BY ADMIN STAFF. <WOS 73
INVESTIGATION OF,IN @49@ DULLES COMMITTEE BLAMED CIA FOR FAILURE TO COORDINATE INFO AS ENVISAGED IN NATIONAL SECURITY ACT OF 1947. <WOS 34
INVESTIGATION OF,IN @71@ SCHLESINGER REPORT NOTED THAT ALTHOUGH PROVISION OF ANALYSIS TO POLICY MAKERS WAS MAJOR PURPOSE OF INTEL~ PRODUCTION OF INTEL WAS REFERRED TO AS ^STEPCHILD OF COMMUNITY.^ IT HAS BEEN TRADITIONALLY OVERSHADOWED BY GLAMOR OF CLANDESTINE ACTIVITIES AND LOVE OF EXOTIC COLLECTION SYSTEMS. IN 85 ADMIRAL TURNER REFERRED TO IT AS ACHILLES HEEL OF INTEL. IT IS CIA DIRECTORATE WHICH HAS SMALLEST BUDGET~ YET ITS SCOPE IS GLOBAL~ WITH INTEREST IN POLITICAL AND MILITARY AS WELL AS ECONOMIC AFFAIRS ALL OVER THE WORLD. SCIENTIFIC REPORTING IS LARGELY LEFT TO THE DIRECTORATE OF SCIENCE AND TECHNOLOGY. <WOS 32-33
