INVESTIGATION OF,IN ITS @75@  INVESTIGATION OF CIA~ CONGRESS ACCEPTED SECRECY RULES OF FORD ADMINISTRATION~ THUS HAVING TO PROVE ITSELF WORTHY OF RECEIVING INFO CLASSIFIED BY EXECUTIVE BRANCH. CIA REQUIRED INVESTIGATIVE STAFF TO WORK AT AGENCY AND REFUSED TO ALLOW SENSITIVE MATERIAL TO BE PHYSICALLY TAKEN TO CONGRESS. <NA 5/22/76 616
INVESTIGATION OF,INDIA~ @98@ A U.S. SATELLITE DEPICTED ACTIVITY AT INDIA'S REMOTE DESERT NUCLEAR TEST SITE~ BUT OFFICIALS FAILED TO DISCERN THAT INDIA WAS PREPARING TO CONDUCT THE [NUCLEAR BLASTS]. EVEN WHEN ^CLEAR-CUT^ EVIDENCE OF THE PREPARATIONS WAS RECORDED BY A SATELLITE~ SIX HOURS BEFORE THE TESTS~ NO CIA WARNING WAS ISSUED BECAUSE THE U.S. ANALYSTS RESPONSIBLE FOR TRACKING THE INDIAN NUCLEAR PROGRAM HAD NOT EXPECTED THE TESTS AND WERE NOT ON ALERT. THEY DID NOT SEE THE PICTURES UNTIL THEY ARRIVED AT WORK. CLINTON DID NOT LEARN OF THIS UNTIL AFTER THE BLASTS HAD OCCURRED~ WHEN NEWS SERVICES CARRIED ACCOUNTS OF A PUBLIC ACKNOWLEDGMENT BY INDIA'S PRIME MINISTER ATAL BIHARI VAJPAYEE. WHEN THE WHITE HOUSE ASKED CIA FOR DETAILS~ IT HAD NONE. THE BLASTS IGNITED FIERCE CRITICISM FROM U.S. POLICYMAKERS~ AND PROMPTED TWO CONGRESSIONAL OVERSIGHT COMMITTEES AND THE CIA TO LAUNCH PROBES OF THE AGENCY'S CONDUCT DURING THE PRECEDING WEEKS AND MONTHS. SEN. RICHARD C. SHELBY~ WHO CHAIRS THE INTEL COMMITTEE~ CONDEMNED THE IC'S CONDUCT~ CALLING THE EPISODE ^A COLOSSAL FAILURE^ THAT BETRAYED A ^DREADFULLY INADEQUATE JOB...^ WE CANNOT MUST NOT TOLERATE SUCH FAILURE ON THE PART OF THE IC~^ HE SAID. DCI TENET APPOINTED A TEAM TO [INVESTIGATE]. THE TEAM IS TO BE HEADED BY RETIRED VICE ADM. DAVID E. JEREMIAH~ A FORMER VICE CHAIRMAN OF THE JOINT CHIEFS OF STAFF~ AND REPORT ITS FINDINGS WITHIN 10 DAYS. AMONG THE ISSUES TO BE EXAMINED: IF CIA'S REGIONAL POLITICAL AND MILITARY ANALYSTS OVERLOOKED CLUES~ WHETHER THE NSA MISSED ANY TELLTALE INFO COLLECTED THROUGH ITS WORLDWIDE ELECTRONIC EAVESDROPPING~ AND HOW SPY SATELLITE OPERATORS AND PHOTO ANALYSTS FAILED TO CATCH SUCH ACTIVITIES AS THE BURIAL OF NUCLEAR DEVICES AND THE ATTACHMENT OF CABLES TO TRANSMIT SCIENTIFIC DATA. <WP 5/13/98 A1
INVESTIGATION OF,INDIA~ @98@ U.S. INTEL ^NEEDS TO BE SCRUBBED^ FROM THE TOP DOWN~ FROM ITS SPIES TO ITS ANALYSTS TO ITS BUREAUCRATIC BARONS~ PER A REPORT INTO THE INABILITY TO FORESEE INDIA'S MAY 11 NUCLEAR TEST. THE DEBACLE REVEALED CHRONIC FAILURES OF IMAGINATION AND PERSONNEL~ FLAWS IN INFO-GATHERING AND ANALYSIS~ AND FAULTY LEADERSHIP AND TRAINING~ PER RETIRED ADM. DAVID JEREMIAH. HIS INVESTIGATION~ GAVE A CORE SAMPLE OF THE STRUCTURAL WEAKNESSES IN U.S. INTEL THAT GO FAR BEYOND THE QUESTION OF INDIA. JEREMIAH REPORTED SOBERING REALITIES ABOUT CIA AND ITS SISTER SERVICES: -- CIA HAD NO SPIES WORTHY OF THE NAME IN INDIA. -- ITS ABILITY TO PRY INFO OUT OF PEOPLE IS WEAK WORLDWIDE. -- THE NATION'S SPY SATELLITES PRODUCE FAR TOO MUCH INFO FOR OVERWORKED AND UNDERTRAINED INTEL ANALYSTS. -- IN INDIA~ SATELLITES AND ANALYSTS ALIKE FAILED TO FOCUS ON THE NUCLEAR TEST SITE~ DESPITE CLEAR CLUES THAT A NUCLEAR TEST WAS COMING. SENIOR INTEL OFFICIALS DISCOUNTED THOSE CLUES AND DID NOT ORDER THEIR UNDERLINGS TO EXAMINE THEM. U.S. POLICY-MAKERS AND INTEL OFFICIALS HAD AN ^UNDERLYING MIND-SET^ THAT INDIA WOULD NOT TEST ITS NUCLEAR WEAPONS. THAT FIXED IDEA WAS UNAFFECTED BY INDIA'S NEWLY ELECTED HINDU NATIONALIST LEADERS OPENLY VOWING TO DEPLOY THE BOMB. JEREMIAH~ DESCRIBED A KIND OF INTELLECTUAL LAZINESS AT THE INTEL SERVICES. ^YOU NEED TO HAVE A CONTRARIAN VIEW.^ CIA'S MANAGERS WERE PASSIVE. CIA NEEDS MANY MORE ANALYSTS WITH BETTER TRAINING AND SHARPER SKILLS. IT SHOULD BRING IN OUTSIDE EXPERTS TO ANALYZE MAJOR EVENTS. IT MUST BE ^MUCH MORE AGGRESSIVE IN THINKING THROUGH HOW THE OTHER GUY THOUGHT^ -- BREAKING OUT OF AMERICAN POLITICAL AND CULTURAL PATTERNS TO GRASP THE WAYS IN WHICH THE REST OF THE WORLD THINKS. RARELY HAS A REPORT COMMISSIONED BY CIA DRAWN SUCH SWIFT AND SWEEPING CONCLUSIONS. GORDON OEHLER~ WHO RETIRED LAST YEAR AS DIRECTOR OF THE CIA'S NONPROLIFERATION CENTER~ SAID THE GROUP OF INTEL ANALYSTS WHO INTERPRET SPY SATELLITE PHOTOS IS A FAR LESS SKILLED GROUP THAN IT WAS AT THE END OF THE COLD WAR. ANALYSTS NOW HAVE AN AVERAGE OF ABOUT 18 MONTHS' EXPERIENCE IN THEIR HIGHLY TECHNICAL TASKS~ SAID JEFFREY HARRIS~ A RECENTLY RETIRED DIRECTOR OF THE NRO. OEHLER SAID THE ^CONTRARIAN VIEWS^ ARE SOMETIMES DISREGARDED~ WHICH DISCOURAGES FRESH THINKING. JEREMIAH~ RECOMMENDED THE DCI MAKE CHANGES TO IMPROVE THE WAYS CIA AND [THE IC] GATHER INFO~ ANALYZE THAT INFO~ MANAGE THEIR EMPLOYEES AND TRAIN NEW PEOPLE. <NYT 6/3/98
